Citizenship Act, RSC 1985, c C-29
5. (1) The Minister grants citizenship to any person who:
(a) requests it;
(b) is at least eighteen years old;
(c) is a permanent resident within the meaning of subsection 2(1) of the
Immigration and Refugee Protection Act
and has, in the four years preceding the date of his application, resided in Canada for at least three years in total, the duration of his residence being calculated as follows:
(i) half a day for each day of residence in Canada before admission as a permanent resident,
(ii) one day for each day of residence in Canada after admission as a permanent resident;
(d) has sufficient knowledge of one of the official languages ​​of Canada;
(e) has sufficient knowledge of Canada and the responsibilities and benefits conferred by citizenship;
(f) is not subject to a removal order and is not the subject of a declaration of the Governor in Council made under section 20.
[...]
(3) For humanitarian reasons, the Minister has the discretionary power to exempt:
(a) in all cases, the conditions set out in paragraph (1)(d) or (e);
(b) in the case of a minor, conditions relating to either age or length of residence in Canada set out in paragraphs (1)(b) and (c), respectively, or to the taking of the oath of citizenship;
(c) in the case of a person incapable of understanding the significance of the oath of citizenship due to mental deficiency, the requirement to take that oath.
Special cases
(4) Despite other provisions of this Act, the Minister has the discretionary power to grant citizenship to any person in order to remedy a particular and unusual situation of distress or to reward exceptional services rendered to Canada.
